@node "Reason" "The motive behind Sample-X"
@{fg shine}TG300@{fg text} is the ultimate Yamaha TG300 patch editor for the Amiga. It allows you
to edit most of the sound parameters from the computer. Therefore, you no
longer have to be hunched over your synth, using that thumb wheel and four
cursor keys.

This product is a result of becoming fed up with using the front panel of my
TG300 to tweak sounds. This tone module has loads of sound creation
potential but the interface is too restricting. With this new patch editor
those restrictions vanish. All the parameters can be easily adjusted on the
computer screen.

I did think about doing a universal patch editor, but then I may never have
finished the software... universal editors have to be incredibly well
designed. I don't particularly want to concentrate on coding patch editors.
I want to make music.

Bye
        Sheun Olatunbosun 15-5-98
@endnode

@node "SystemReq" "System requirements"
@{fg shine}TG300@{fg text} requires @{b}Workbench 2.04+@{ub} and of course a @{b}Yamaha TG300@{ub} tone module.
Owners of @{b}XG@{ub} units such as the DB50XG or MU10 should be able to use it, but
they must have their unit set to TG300B mode emulation.

Without an external sound unit, the patch edittor is of little use, unless
you want to look at the gorgeous interface :-).

The @{b}midi.library@{ub} is also required.
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"
@{b}TG300@{ub} has the following features


   - System, Part, Voice, Drum, Effect editing
   - Suspend operation
   - Intuitive GUI layout
   - Retargettable MIDI ports
   - Snapshot facility
   - MIDI port reconfigure
@endnode

@node "GetStart" "Getting Started"
Run the installation script which simply copies the "newtopaz" font to your
FONTS directory (this font is so much nicer than the default Workbench
one).

You can start@{b} TG300@{ub} from the CLI by entering 'TG300' or double clicking on
its icon from Workbench. TG300 will then attempt to open on its own screen.

(@{i}If TG300 fails to start then make sure that you have the midi.library
installed in the LIBS: directory and the newtopaz font in the FONTS:@{ui})

Connect the MIDI OUT port of an external keyboard to the MIDI IN port of the
MIDI interface of the Amiga. Then connect the MIDI OUT of this interface to
the MIDI IN port of the TG300.

@{i}(If you wish to dump data from the TG300 to your computer then you'll need
to connect the MIDI OUT of the TG300 to the MIDI IN of the Amiga. Where do
you connect the keyboard? Well, you'll need a MIDI switch box or MIDI
merger)@{ui}


That's it! Start tweaking and listen to the changes.

Right, all that remains is to explain the meaning of the various features of
@{"TG300" link "TG300Screen" 0}.
@endnode

